  "text": "Django CharField max_length validation and enforcement spans multiple components:\n\n**Field-Level Validation** (django/db/models/fields/__init__.py:1204-1250):\nThe CharField class validates max_length at the model field level in two ways:\n1. In __init__ (line 1209): Adds a MaxLengthValidator to the field's validators list if max_length is not None\n2. In _check_max_length_attribute (line 1226): System check that validates max_length is a positive integer\n\n**Validator Implementation** (django/core/validators.py:489):\nMaxLengthValidator is the core validation class that enforces max_length constraints. It's instantiated and added to CharField.validators by the field.\n\n**Form Field Validation** (django/forms/fields.py:275-288):\nThe form CharField independently implements max_length validation:\n1. Stores max_length attribute (line 279)\n2. Adds MaxLengthValidator to form field validators (line 287)\n3. Sets HTML maxlength widget attribute (line 302-304) for client-side enforcement\n\n**Model to Form Field Mapping** (django/db/models/fields/__init__.py:1300-1309):\nCharField.formfield() method passes max_length to the form field, creating a chain of validation.\n\n**Database Backend Type Definition**:\nmax_length is enforced at the database level through type definitions:\n- MySQL (django/db/backends/mysql/base.py:116): \"varchar(%(max_length)s)\"\n- PostgreSQL (django/db/backends/postgresql/base.py:111): Uses _get_varchar_column function (line 86-89) which returns \"varchar(%(max_length)s)\" for non-null max_length\n- SQLite (django/db/backends/sqlite3/base.py:71): Uses _get_varchar_column function (line 43-46)\n- Oracle (django/db/backends/oracle/base.py:131): \"NVARCHAR2(%(max_length)s)\"\n\n**Database Column Type Generation** (django/db/models/fields/__init__.py:857-886):\nThe db_type() method retrieves the database backend's data_types dictionary entry for CharField, substituting max_length and other parameters via db_type_parameters() (line 840-841).\n\n**Migration Auto-Detection** (django/db/migrations/autodetector.py:1252-1378):\nThe MigrationAutodetector.generate_altered_fields() method:\n1. Compares old and new field definitions using deep_deconstruct() (line 1334-1335)\n2. When field deconstructed forms differ, creates AlterField operations (line 1366-1371)\nmax_length changes trigger AlterField operations because they appear in the field deconstruction.\n\n**AlterField Operation** (django/db/migrations/operations/fields.py:204-271):\nAlterField represents a field alteration in migrations. Its database_forwards method (line 235-245) calls schema_editor.alter_field().\n\n**Schema Editor Execution** (django/db/backends/base/schema.py:847-937):\nThe SchemaEditor.alter_field() method:\n1. Retrieves db_parameters for old and new fields (line 858-861), which includes the db_type with max_length\n2. Calls _alter_field() to execute database-specific SQL changes\n3. The actual SQL generation uses the new max_length through db_type()\n\nThis comprehensive chain ensures CharField max_length is validated at model level, form level, and database level, with migration detection to track changes."
